9. The satires as a biographical source. When we look into the satires for information with regard to the life of their author, we should use discretion, for a poet is not necessarily his own biographer. Many a picture which he presents may be purely literary, due to the influence of department or of other writers, and may have no existence in fact. Even what seems to have a direct person-al reference should not in all cases be regarded as authoritative. We may reasonably expect, however, to draw from the satires some inferences with regard to the poet's education and char- acter² and to fix approximately the period of his literary activity.
